<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-297-232  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 297 232.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  April 24 1989 v3 n17 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making sensible cuts in the defense budget. (In Perspective)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reed, Fred.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mikhail Gorbachev's recent actions suggest that defense cutbacksmight be an appropriate US response.andP;  But suppose Gorbachev doesnot last? If Congress cuts the defense budget before we arecertain about Soviet intentions, what should our military do? Hereare some suggestions: missile submarines deter a sneak attack, sokeep them; cut pricey systems that do things already done in otherways - for example, B1, B2, Star Wars and MX; and push hard forcheap, expendable weapons that use tricky sensors and computers -antitank missiles, air-to-air and ground-to-air missiles, andcruise missiles.andP;  We are in less danger now, and technologicaldrift and economic concomitants seem in our favor.andP;  Another pointto consider is this: the Soviet Union has been passedtechnologically by Pacific Rim nations, which already can designand manufacture computers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryBudgetingUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States. CongressSoviet UnionSecurityPacific Rim countries.andO;Person:    Gorbachev, Mikhail (military policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>